g.title: j425246079
g.text: For you, always.

g.title: j2163474382
g.text: I'm *really* sorry, I can't right now. [End.]

g.title: j1321569449

g.title: j1555700564
g.text: Do you know who the Hooded Woman is?

g.title: j2937826639

g.text: La Flaca?

g.text: Is that your name for Death?

g.title: j2937826639->j589562578

g.title: j2030483093
g.text: Not quite.

g.title: j391765126
g.text: +5 Chemistry

g.title: j1410106533
g.text: She’s Death. Also one of the Aspects of Lua, depending on which tradition you follow. She’s the one who comes and tucks you into bed once the knockabout day of Life is over, kisses you goodnight, and sings you to sleep.

g.title: j2853999336
g.text: Hah. Speaking to our dear Lettie, I see. Yes.

g.title: j1537167290
g.text: Yes, actually.

g.title: j2471871062
g.text: You weren’t kidding about being melancholy, were you?

g.title: j1399298749
g.text: This is going to be one of those "get comfy, Drifter, this is going to take a minute" conversations, isn't it?

g.title: j2789307753
g.text: Mate. Everything Entrati gave us, the power, the strength, the armour plated arses… I’d trade it all for one crumb of reassurance that death isn’t the end.

g.title: j657062911
g.text: ... it was going to be.

g.title: j3947332760
g.text: I’ve tried. I don’t feel good about admitting this, but sometimes when we’ve been out on patrol and there’s been fighting, I look into the minds of the dying and try to go through the process with them. If there’s any light at all at the end of the tunnel, I just want to see it.

g.title: j3505580948
g.text: Forget it. I'm sure you have more important things to do.

g.title: j501825049
g.text: Eleanor, that’s ghoulish. You have no right.

g.title: j3447050247
g.text: Do you try to comfort them at all?

g.title: j3169668593
g.text: I know. I KNOW.

g.title: j1936900783
g.text: I did, once. What’s the harm, right? They’re dying anyway. It was this young Scaldra trooper. She was coming for me and I shot her in the chest.

g.title: j1756206850
g.text: I tell myself I was trying to help but the truth is I just wanted to see. You're right. It was ghoulish.

g.title: j4076572434
g.text: I knelt down by her side as she gargled out her lifeblood and tried to tell her it was okay, the pain was coming to an end, soon she’d be with her family who had gone before, all the placid, pacifying stuff you think of when there’s a deathbed service to be held.

g.title: j118907768
g.text: She was terrified. What was left of her conscious self was scrabbling around like a rat in a water tank. When she felt me in her mind with her, she tried to cling on. She begged me to help. Underneath it all was this… I don’t even know what you’d call it…

g.title: j3965635333
g.text: Hope?

g.title: j1064481610
g.text: Fear?

g.title: j1715808920
g.text: Denial?

g.title: j3722611115
g.text: Denial. She didn’t believe she could be dying. And why would she? She’d always been there before. How could death be taking her away now?

g.title: j2365043416
g.text: Every day of your life, you take YOURSELF for granted. You’re there when you wake up and you’re there when you sleep. You live out your entire life in a house made of You. You never once go outside, because you can’t.

g.title: j3287986900
g.text: Then one day, you hear the house being knocked down.

g.title: j565266169
g.text: Why didn’t you help her?

g.title: j4208371
g.text: Did you stay with her until the end?

g.title: j4126408643
g.text: What would you have had me do? Call Lettie over? Heal the gaping chest wound? All because I saw what this one was going through, up close?

g.title: j1927762592
g.text: Yeah. I was scared shitless. As she felt herself slipping over the edge, I was sure I’d be dragged down with her. I could feel this undertow tugging at me.

g.title: j2588095516
g.text: With the Scaldra it's kill or be killed. They don't offer us the luxury of mercy.

g.title: j1119966825
g.text: I had to stay, though. I couldn’t abandon her to die alone.

g.title: j2897264640
g.text: Though I guess she did, in the end. I couldn’t take that last step with her.

g.title: j3543878391
g.text: What did you learn from the experience?

g.title: j3335883679
g.text: So did you see what you were hoping to see?

g.title: j2310908529
g.text: I learned nothing.

g.title: j1258891649
g.text: No.

g.title: j2302128596
g.text: She did, though. She saw her mother’s face, the kids she went to school with, her cat, some cousin who drowned. But they weren’t presences, or spirits. Just memories, forced to the surface by a dying brain desperately hunting for something to cling to.

g.title: j153167211
g.text: Then the house of her identity began to come apart around her. Right before she died, she opened her eyes wide. I think in that second, for the first time in her life, she truly understood what death actually is.

g.title: j2951025054
g.text: Dying person understands what death is. What an insight, Eleanor.

g.title: j1565124938
g.text: What do you mean? Everyone knows what death is.

g.title: j4061949891
g.text: Look. Next time you feel the need to call me out on my bullshit, don't feel you have to sit through it first.

g.title: j1712814661
g.text: No. We think we know what it is, but all of our experiences are from the outside.

g.title: j2457720721
g.text: Nobody's forcing you to talk to me. Bye.

g.title: j1582508651
g.text: Her whole life she was like a woman living in a house with no lights, and all she had was a flashlight. She’d shine the light of her awareness on one spot or another. A memory, a task, an interaction.

g.title: j3749165992
g.text: She’d move from room to room, explore the cellars in her sleep, but always it would be a closed, finite process. Do you follow me?

g.title: j1975441186
g.text: Not really, but carry on.

g.title: j2766843207
g.text: Yes.

g.title: j849021094
g.text: Then when the house was demolished and her persona fell to pieces around her, suddenly the flashlight wasn’t shining on a wall or a book or a couch. It was shining up into the infinite sky. Her awareness blazed into the endless without the obstacle of herself standing in the way.

g.title: j457757066
g.text: But awareness dies when the body dies. What you experienced was just a spasm in her dying brain.

g.title: j3409095290
g.text: You think ‘awareness’ is who we really are and the rest is just a shell?

g.title: j4072343503
g.text: Wow. So deep. You shot someone and then violated her privacy.

g.title: j2683423694
g.text: I've tried to tell myself that, many times.

g.title: j2754226377
g.text: +5 Chemistry

g.title: j1299211261
g.text: I can't believe it was nothing more than the brain shutting down. It felt like the soul breaking free.

g.title: j2249155288
g.text: I know it doesn’t make any kind of sense. It feels so counterintuitive, the idea that we are a point of view first and a personality second. All I know is that’s how it felt to be with a human soul as it passed from life to death.

g.title: j1400409473
g.text: How do you feel about all of that?

g.title: j3086770544
g.text: Comforted? I like the idea that something of us survives. I love thinking that death isn’t about being deleted from the universe, but having everything deleted that separates you from the universe.

g.title: j2749888708
g.text: But what makes us US isn’t just raw awareness. It’s memory, emotion, opinion, all sorts of layers. When you lose all that you’re losing a real person, even if that spark somehow survives.

g.title: j337052147
g.text: I know.

g.title: j2162053872
g.text: Honestly, this is why I wanted to talk to you about void ghosts and Cephalons and all of that stuff from your time. I need to know if we ever get the chance to communicate with people we’ve lost.

g.title: j588225993
g.text: Real communication, not some hologram crap. The kind that lets you know definitively what the person thought.

g.title: j1058440983
g.text: No, not really. Even in the future, the people we've lost are... for better or worse? Just... gone.

g.title: j1789519361
g.text: Eleanor, get to the point. Who did you lose?

g.title: j766513707
g.text: I see. Maybe there are some doors we can never open. Maybe that's for the best.

g.title: j2174016389
g.text: His name was Christopher. He was Arthur’s best friend.

g.title: j1360941920
g.text: We were engaged. I thought I was in love with him.

g.title: j3755064947
g.text: Boolean EleanorChristopher1 is now true.

g.title: j2511904030
g.text: +10 Chemistry

g.title: j499951188
g.text: I’m sorry. I can’t do this. I’ll talk to you another time.
